# Git workflow

## Default branch and integration

- **Feature branches** merge via pull request into **`dev`**, not `main`.
- **Automated agents** (subagents, cloud agent, and similar): work only on a **feature branch** in the **primary clone**. **`coding-clanker`** creates or reuses the branch and implements locally. **`github-clanker`** commits and pushes **only that branch** and opens PRs with **`gh pr create --base dev`** (or equivalent). Agents must **not** push to **`dev`** or **`main`**, merge into those branches, or commit while checked out on **`dev`** or **`main`**.
- **Humans** merge approved PRs into **`dev`** and later promote **`dev` â†’ `main`**.
- **Never** target **`main`** with agent-created PRs, direct pushes to `main`, or agent-driven merges into `main`.

## Human command surface

- The intended human workflow is: issue outside Cursor, **`/plan-from-issue #n`**, the accepted planâ€™s **Build** button, **`/build-and-run [app]`**, **`/code-review`**, **`/ui-review`**, and **`/github-publish #n`**.
- Cursor does **not** expose a repo-local way to hard-bind the Build button to a named subagent. This repo therefore steers Build toward **`coding-clanker`** with rules, plan handoff wording, and subagent descriptions.

## No Git worktrees (hard rule)

- **Automated agents** must **not** create extra checkouts with **`git worktree add`** (no sibling folders like `â€¦-issue-<n>` for parallel trees). Work only in the userâ€™s primary clone; use a normal feature branch.
- Local **`beforeShellExecution`** hook denies **`git worktree add`** so agent shells cannot create worktrees in-repo.

## Coding-clanker-only implementation (hard rule)

- After plan acceptance, Build starts immediately and **all implementation must go through `coding-clanker`**.
- The primary agent must not directly implement feature code in Agent mode or Plan mode.
- The accepted planâ€™s **Build** button is the intended path. If a manual fallback is ever needed, the coding-clanker handoff must include an issue reference (**`#<n>`**) so local hooks can update GitHub status labels.
- Coding-clanker handoff should include an accepted plan path or approved plan summary saved in the workspace.
- `coding-clanker` creates or reuses the feature branch, implements, runs **`npm run build`**, and stops before commit, push, or PR work.

## GitHub publish (hard rule)

- Commit, push, and PR creation or update must be delegated to **`github-clanker`**.
- `github-clanker` runs only after human feature review or test via **`/build-and-run`** and any manual review-agent passes are ready.
- `github-clanker` may commit and push only the current feature branch and must target **`dev`** with the PR.

## Review agents (hard rule)

- **`code-review-clanker`** and **`ui-review-clanker`** are report-only.
- Humans invoke review agents manually via **`/code-review`** and **`/ui-review`**; they are not the automatic start of Build.
- If review finds issues, the parent routes implementation back through **`coding-clanker`** by reusing the accepted planâ€™s **Build** step on the same feature branch.

## GitHub label workflow (required)

- Only one status label should exist on an issue at a time: **`status:todo`**, **`status:in-progress`**, **`status:in-review`**, or **`status:done`**.
- New issues start as **`status:todo`**.
- On `coding-clanker` start, hooks set issue label **`status:in-progress`** and remove the other status labels.
- On successful `coding-clanker` completion (local implementation ready), hooks set **`status:in-review`** and remove the other status labels.
- On merge to `dev`, GitHub Actions set **`status:done`**, remove the other status labels, and close the issue.
- In this workflow, **`status:in-review`** means local implementation is ready for human or review-agent feedback, or a PR is open and awaiting review.
- In this workflow, **`status:done`** means **merged to `dev`**, not human-tested and not promoted to `main`.
- If `#<n>` is missing from coding-clanker delegation, hook enforcement blocks coding-clanker startup.

## PR body contract (required)

- Every PR must include:

  ```md
  ## Summary
  - Bullet list of what changed

  ## Test plan
  - [ ] Verification step(s)

  Closes #<n>
  ```

- `github-clanker` creates the PR with this shape and refreshes the **Summary** after each meaningful push via `gh pr edit`.
- `Closes #<n>` or `Fixes #<n>` must survive every PR body update so merge automation can still set **`status:done`**.
- Local shell hooks currently enforce PR base and issue-closing keywords. The **Summary** contract is enforced by `github-clanker`, the PR template, and review discipline rather than brittle shell parsing.

## Promotion to main

- **`dev` â†’ `main`** is a **human-controlled** release step after checks on `dev`.
- Agents deliver work via PRs into `dev`; they do not complete the production promotion.

## GitHub settings note

- Protect `dev` and `main` in GitHub. Require pull requests and the required checks documented in [docs/project_init.md](@docs/project_init.md).
- GitHub Actions in this repo currently cover merge-to-`dev` label/closure automation and branch deletion, plus CI checks under [.github/workflows/](@.github/workflows/).
